decision d_33847bd84f6f0881 target=file subject=crates/queue/src/dkim.rs status=accepted source="human:justin" basis=- title="Publish DKIM p= as X.509 SPKI DER, not mail_auth's native PKCS#1 output" detail="DMARC aggregate report from google.com (susumu.dev, selector=litterae, 2026-07-19) showed dkim=fail while SPF passed. dig confirmed the published TXT record was syntactically well-formed DKIM1/k=rsa but decoded as a bare PKCS#1 RSAPublicKey DER (flat SEQUENCE{INTEGER modulus, INTEGER exponent}, 270 bytes) rather than X.509 SubjectPublicKeyInfo. Root cause: mail_auth::dkim::generate::DkimKeyPair::generate_rsa's public_key() calls to_pkcs1_der(), and litterae's dns_txt_record() base64'd that directly. mail_auth's own verifier code tries SPKI first and only falls back to PKCS#1, confirming SPKI is the real-world-expected format; Google's verifier evidently isn't lenient about it. Fix: dns_txt_record() now re-encodes public_der through rsa::pkcs1::DecodeRsaPublicKey -> rsa::pkcs8::EncodePublicKey before publishing, added rsa as a direct queue dependency for this. Private key / signing path (RsaKey::from_key_der(PrivateKeyDer::Pkcs1)) is untouched -- only the DNS-facing encoding changed. Operator action still required: republish the corrected TXT record at litterae._domainkey.susumu.dev from the admin panel; the DKIM key itself was not rotated, only its published encoding.";
